n","1400–Male":"1400–Overleden","1330–Male":"1330–Overleden","1334–Female":"1334–Overleden","ABT    1400":"circa 1400","ABT    1377":"circa 1377","1330":"1330","1396":"1396","1394":"1394","1381":"1381","1370":"1370","1358":"1358","1334":"1334","1400":"1400","1356":"1356","1377":"1377","Abt 1396":"circa 1396","about 1394":"circa 1394","Llanwrthwl, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llanwrthwl, Breconshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cantref, Breconshire, Wales":"Cantref, Breconshire, Wales","of Glyntawe,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Glyntawe, Breconshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Llandilofawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llandilofawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales","{Blddn ap Mnrch}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Italië"},"en":{"ABT    1377–":"about 1377–Deceased","1356–Male":"1356–Deceased","1358–Male":"1358–Deceased","1370–Male":"1370–Deceased","1377–Male":"1377–Deceased","1381–Female":"1381–Deceased","1394–Male":"1394–Deceased","1396–Male":"1396–Deceased","1400–Male":"1400–Deceased","1330–Male":"1330–Deceased","1334–Female":"1334–Deceased","ABT    1400":"about 1400","ABT    1377":"about 1377","1330":"1330","1396":"1396","1394":"1394","1381":"1381","1370":"1370","1358":"1358","1334":"1334","1400":"1400","1356":"1356","1377":"1377","Abt 1396":"about 1396","about 1394":"about 1394","Llanwrthwl, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llanwrthwl, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Cantref, Breconshire, Wales":"Cantref, Breconshire, Wales","of Glyntawe,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Glyntawe, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Llandilofawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llandilofawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales","{Blddn ap Mnrch}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Italy","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Llywelyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(Welsh)  See  Llewelyn ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewelyn","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."]}]},{"name":"Ddu\"","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 竇, meaning ‘hole’ in ancient Chinese: (i) adopted as a surname by Yue Zhu and Yue Long, two sons of Shao Kang, the sixth king of the Xia dynasty (2070–1600  BC ). Yue Zhu and Yue Long are said to have adopted Dou (竇) (meaning ‘hole’) as a surname because their pregnant grandmother had escaped from a rebellion through a hole in the wall before giving birth to their father, Shao Kang, who later recaptured the throne. (ii) traced back to the Dou (竇) family from the Di ethnic group and some other families from the Xianbei ethnic group in ancient China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 豆, denoting an ancient stemmed cup of bowl: (i) traced back to some inhabitants in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) adopted as the surname by the Chi Xiao Dou (赤小豆) and Dou Lu (豆盧) family from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 鈄, referring to a type of ancient vessel for drinking wine: said to be borne by the descendants of the Duke Kang of Qi (died 379  BC ), who was ousted from his throne in the state of Qi and sent into exile. It was said that he was forced to use the vessel Dou (鈄) to cook food during his exile, and some of his descendants inherited Dou as the surname to memorize this period."],"variants":[{"name":"Du","meanings":["‘Wealthy’."]},{"name":"Dau","meanings":["From Old Norse <i>dagr</i> ‘day’."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Llywelyn \" Ddu\" ap Dafydd was born about 1377, in Glyntawe, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Dafydd ap Hywel, was 49 and his mother, Gwenyfer, was 45. He had at least 3 sons with Mrs. Llywelyn Ddu ap Dafydd."},"et":{"ABT    1377–":"umbes 1377–Surnud","1356–Male":"1356–Surnud","1358–Male":"1358–Surnud","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1377–Male":"1377–Surnud","1381–Female":"1381–Surnud","1394–Male":"1394–Surnud","1396–Male":"1396–Surnud","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1334–Female":"1334–Surnud","ABT    1400":"umbes 1400","ABT    1377":"umbes 1377","1330":"1330","1396":"1396","1394":"1394","1381":"1381","1370":"1370","1358":"1358","1334":"1334","1400":"1400","1356":"1356","1377":"1377","Abt 1396":"umbes 1396","about 1394":"umbes 1394","Llanwrthwl, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llanwrthwl, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Cantref, Breconshire, Wales":"Cantref, Breconshire, Wales","of Glyntawe,Defynnog,Breconshire,Wales":"Glyntawe, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Llandilofawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llandilofawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales","{Blddn ap Mnrch}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Itaalia"},"fi":{"ABT    1377–":"noin 1377–Kuollut","1356–Male":"1356–Kuollut","1358–Male":"1358–Kuollut","1370–Male":"1370–Kuollut","1377–Male":"1377–Kuollut","1381–Female":"1381–Kuollut","1394–Male":"1394–Kuollut","1396–Male":"1396–Kuollut","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1334–Female":"1334–Kuollut","ABT    1400":"noin 1400","ABT    1377":"noin 1377","1330":"1330","1396":"1396","1394":"1394","1381":"1381","1370":"1370","1358":"1358","1334":"1334","1400":"1400","1356":"1356","1377":"1377","Abt 1396":"noin 1396","about 1394":"noin 1394","Llanwrthwl, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llanwrthwl, Breconshire, Wales, Yhdis